>In article <11156.204.uupcb@ssr.com> dick.zeitlin%acc1bbs@ssr.com (Dick Zeitlin) writes:

>> D> .It wouldn't greatly surprise me.  As I understand it, new Federal
>>  > .regulations next year will ban the use of radar detectors by these 18
>>  > .wheelers.  Now they'll not only control transmitting, but RECEIVING as well
>> 
>> The feds have been attempting to control reception since the passage of
>> ECPA.

>Keep in mind that radar detectors have a small transmitter too.  (I'm *NOT*
>defending the right to take them away, but merely pointing out that they are not
>strictly passive receptors.

What do you mean?  They are passive receivers.  Thhe only radiation is a
byproduct of the signal conversion process, as it is wwith every other 
receiver.

One of the basic tenets of communication law (up to the passaage of ECPA)
was that you can receive **ANYTHING**.  Some things you couldn't talk about,
some you could, but you could receive anything you had the technology to
grab.

